nding memo while claiming that the =E2=80=9Cfederal funding freeze=E2=80=9D=
 still stood. As Leigh Ann notes, this is just the latest example of Trump =
testing the limits of his presidential powers more aggressively than at any=
 point during his first term, all with the tacit (and often explicit) appro=
val of congressional Republicans. All presidents try to expand their power,=
 but Trump believes he has Congress and the Supreme Court behind him=E2=80=
=94and
he could be right. A little more than a week into the new administration, o=
ne thing=E2=80=99s already clear, as Stephen Griffin, who teaches constitut=
ional law at Tulane, told Leigh Ann: =E2=80=9CConstitutionally, we=E2=80=99=
re looking at a very volatile situation.=E2=80=9D

